orth it in Barcelona?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "The essentials are the Sagrada Família and Park Güell. Of the Passeig de Gràcia houses, pick one — Casa Batlló for its colour and dragon-back roof, or La Pedrera (Casa Milà) for its sculpted stone and rooftop chimneys. The lesser-known Bellesguard is a quiet bonus for Gaudí enthusiasts."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "Is Barcelona a good base for day trips?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "One of the best. Within an hour or so by train you can reach Girona and the Dalí Theatre-Museum in Figueres, the Roman city of Tarragona and the seaside town of Sitges, and Gaudí's experimental Colonia Güell crypt — each an easy, rewarding day out and covered in its own post."}}, {"@type": "Question", "name": "What should you watch out for in Barcelona?", "acceptedAnswer": {"@type": "Answer", "text": "Pickpockets — Barcelona is notorious, especially on La Rambla, the metro and in the Boqueria crowds. Keep your bag in front and your phone away. Also book all the major Gaudí sites ahead, and pre-arrange transport if you have an early-morning flight."}}]}]};
